highlights.description: Actions speak louder than words
Arlene says Madison is still a relatively safe city compared to some places and certainly much more diverse now
Daryl tells a story about telling a off-color joke to a black high schooler on a trip back from Boys State
When I was in the military in the South I almost got into a fight with a bus driver for sitting in the back
When I was a child in Madison people wanted my parents to sign a petition to get rid of the first black people in our neighborhood
In South Madison, prostitution has gone underground
I witnessed a black driver get pulled over by police
Participant asking Host, who is Chinese- American, for her thoughts on the conversation which has focused on racism
I drove across WI in 1972 at height of anti-Vietnam protests-- I had a beard and could feel the hostility in small towns
Brief conversation about how it can be old to be the object of others' curiosity about people unlike oneself
I went to one-room schools for the first 8 years of my education and then high school and in none of those cases did I know any black people
one thing to take from our conversation that you'd like other people to hear... is that there is hope... people are working hard to change things for the better
Daryl criticizing Madison's reputation of being an inclusive city. His points highlight disparities in criminalization and segregation in the city.
Arlene talking about racism in her majority white neighborhood towards the only Black person living in the neighborhood.
Group talking about Northen Wisconsin and the prejudice against Native American groups in the area.
Daryl stating that there is always something to do in Madison.
Comment about racism and the policing/criminalization of Black people
Meetings focused on talking about racial issues do not have Black or Brown folks present.
Ruthanne talking about her experience growing up Chinese in Madison.
Ruthanne talking about a time where her family was the only Chinese family at a restaurant and the reaction of the folks around them

Madison is not as open and diverse as it seems. Black Americans and people of color are disproportionately affected for marijuana possession in comparison to white counterparts. --> Update: People should listen to this because an older white man is acknowledging his privilege.
The role of police in Chicago during the 60's when bigotry was more socially and overtly expressed.
Met diverse ethno-racial folks on campus.  (Does not specify whether they were domestic or international students.)
Did not enjoy being surrounded by colleagues in the lab whom expressed bigotry.  Everyone identified as Catholic.

Is under the impression that police are much better now, with respect to race-relations. 
Acknowledges that her white privilege may inform her understanding of what constitutes "better."
Unintentionally made a joke that could be considered a "black joke" and noticed how it made the black individual react.  Expresses remorse as his actions in this moment continue to bother him today.
Saw how segregation affected quotidian things for his military colleagues.  For his friends this was a normal experience.
How racial integration looked like in Madison neighborhoods at the time and her father serving as an ally.

Prejudice against non-white Americans in the late 70's, particularly in northern Wisconsin against indigenous peoples. --> Update: This was interesting to me because even I tend to forget that in places like rural Wisconsin it may be more likely for folks to have this experience vis-a-vis other ethno-racial folks.
Like many other citizens, Arlene does not have a clear understanding as to why the city of Madison and the town of Madison are not integrated.

Police officer's attitude changes towards the black friend driving the car when he realizes that his friend in the back is the son of a Madison judge.  White privilege. --> Update: People should hear this because it is a direct example of not only white privilege, but also the privilege of having connections to people with power (even if locally.)
Prejudice continues to be and remains institutionalized.

It is unclear what police protocols are in place when encountering situations like this.  A Madison police officer shoots a young black male on his own and by video footage it is not clear whether the officer could have attempted an alternative approach to pacify the situation. --> Update: This is important because even in what is considered a progressive city, Black young men are gunned down by police enforcement.
The university is not necessarily diverse.

Socio-economic and racial disadvantages can result in a late start on education.  It follows you all throughout your adulthood. --> Update: This was worth listening to because this is common amongst poor and working poor communities more generally.  Trying to close the learning gap that follows those whom come from disadvantaged backgrounds becomes harder as one gets older.

People that have an economic advantage are withdrawing their children from schools where disadvantaged ethno-racial students whose first language is not English enroll.  As black and brown enrollment goes up, students with families from middle to upper class backgrounds goes down.
Actively engages in expressing opinions to his representative.
Expresses himself as an ally to communities of color.  Encourages more conversations across cultures.

Expresses being uncomfortable with her own ethno-racial background and becoming more embracing throughout adulthood.  Acknowledges that the Chinese community has not been explicitly targeted in more contemporary times although she has still experienced racism.

The uncomfortable experience of feeling "othered" in public spaces.  --> Update: I thought this was worth listening to because when people of color are observed in such a way it seems as if our uniqueness is on display, like an animal at an exhibit.  Some people are more subtle than others, this is an example where being subtle is not the case.
The shooting of Tony Robinson in Madison.
describing hearing about tony robinson
